	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Looking for good PC sync software</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />So you want something like rsync that works on a Windows LAN and preserves the mtime (last modification date) and birthtime (creation date) of each file.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">Kasumi wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Allow me to sync folders of an unlimited size.</div><br />To make this work, you would need to run this software on a server with unlimited storage space. And if a share can be accessed through the Internet (which you say you don't really need), both the server and each client would need unlimited data transfer to and from the Internet. With even wired home ISPs instituting monthly caps, the latter is becoming harder and harder to get.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Ideally it would work through just the home network.</div><br />How would each computer find the other computers with syncable folders, especially as these computers' IP addresses change? Or does your &quot;super complicated but one time setup&quot; include installing DHCP reservations through the router appliance's administration interface?

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


